is it cuz regardless, itll take u to an address in one of the  8 rows of memory? And there will be no overlap since theres 8 possible ways u can arrange 3 bits,  and 8 places they can refer to
And then referring to an address for writing will then refer to the same address when reading
Really, to give you a simple analogy
I tell you to take an item and place it in box 0
you say ok and you take my item and place it in box 3
Later I ask you to give me back my item at box 0
then you go to box 3 and give me my item
I don't care that you didn't place my item in specifically box 0, I just care that when I asked you to get me back what I have at box 0, you gave me what I gave you originally
so in this case with memory, the same instructions that were asked to be put in at a given address are the same ones that will come out
That's all that a RAM is supposed to do
At the end of the day
RAM has absolutely no knowledge of what's a significant bit
it has no concept of what significance is
That's why this all ends up working out nicely

ye u just want to make sure that you put data in **a** location that is distinct, because we are assuming that the person who is reading/writing the data is aware of where what they want is, would that be a correct way to think abt it?
